<DOC><DOCNO> AP880218-0292 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-PX-02-18-88 2157EST</FILEID><FIRST>u f BC-BusinessHighlights 1stAdd   02-18 0505</FIRST><SECOND>BC-Business Highlights, 1st Add,0528</SECOND><DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   A majority of striking employees at Ford MotorCo.'s British plants voted to accept a two-year contract offer,signaling the end of the country's first major industrial strike inthree years.   The offer represented the first significant union victory inBritain in seven years. Ford made several concessions to end thestrike, which began Feb. 8.   Voter returns Thursday night showed 70 percent of the workers atthe 22 British plants favored the offer. The company said itexpected workers to be back on the job Monday.</TEXT><DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Texaco Inc. plans to sell a stake of about 50percent in its extensive U.S. gulf coast refining operations toSaudi Arabia for more than $1 billion, according to publishedreports.   A final agreement between Petromin, the Saudi Arabian oilholding arm, and Texaco is expected to be reached within a month,the Herald Tribune reported Thursday, quoting an unidentifiedTexaco executive and unidentified Arab oil executives attending anannual conference of the Institute of Petroleum in London.   In White Plains, N.Y., a spokesman at Texaco's headquartersrefused to confirm or deny the accuracy of the report.</TEXT><DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   American Standard Inc.'s board of directorsapproved a multibillion-dollar recapitalization plan, escalatingthe company's battle to thwart the hostile $2.03 billion takeoverbid by Black andamp; Decker Corp.   The plan approved Thursday would pay American Standardstockholders $64 a share in cash and junk bonds and give them stockin the recapitalized company, which would take on a staggering newdebt load to finance the proposal.   American Standard shares rose 50 cents to $67.50 and Black andamp;Decker dipped 12{ cents to $18.87{ on the New York Stock Exchange.</TEXT><DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Severe insider-trading penalties are damagingnew cases by discouraging potential defendants from cooperating, atop official of the Securities and Exchange Commission was quotedas saying.   Gary Lynch, SEC enforcement director and one of the architectsbehind a campaign against Wall Street corruption, was quoted assaying in a television interview that the prospect of imprisonment,civil fines and financial ruin is convincing some people ``it'sbetter to hunker down than cooperate.'' His remarks were to bebroadcast Sunday on ``The Wall Street Journal Report.''</TEXT><DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Federal regulators have ordered an immediatesuspension of the use of an industrial device which has leaked tinyparticles of radioactive polonium at plants around the nation.   The Nuclear Regulatory Commission also ordered the 3M Corp. onThursday to recall for inspection all 45,000 of the suspectdevices, ionizing air guns used to control static electricity andremove dust from product containers.</TEXT><BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE><TEXT>   Stocks declined in late trading Thursday. The Dow Jonesindustrial average dropped 14.58 points to 1,986.41 after closingslightly above 2,000 in the week's first two sessions.   Bond prices rose in reaction to falling commodity prices. Thedollar closed lower in Europe but higher in the United States. Goldprices were mostly down.</TEXT></DOC>